{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506886"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:47:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:47:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2587"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.48,0.13,0.06,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2587"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4853"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44944"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to her GP after waking up this morning and noticing she was having trouble hearing from her right ear. She has never had hearing issues in the past. She has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease and hypertension. She takes aspirin 100mg, perindopril 5mg and atorvastatin 40mg every morning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her tympanic membrane appears normal, there are no foreign bodies in the ear. Rinne\u2019s test demonstrates air conduction louder than bone conduction bilaterally. Weber\u2019s test localises to the left side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gadolinium enhanced MRI head","Prednisolone 1mg/kg to a max of 75mg for 5-7 days","Routine referral to ENT out-patient clinic","Cease aspirin immediately","CT head including the temporal bones"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question demonstrates what is most consistent with idiopathic sensorineural hearing loss. Diagnosis should be based on a history that describes a clear and sudden change or loss in hearing suggests sudden onset or awakening with new hearing loss. Examination demonstrates sensorineural hearing loss (SNHL), as shown by a normal Rinne\u2019s and altered bone conduction on the right (affected side) leading Weber\u2019s to lateralise to the left side. Further confirmation of the diagnosis can be done through audiometric testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment with high dose \u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E1mg/kg to a max of 75mg for 5-7 days\u003C/strong\u003E should be commenced immediately after suspicion of a diagnosis of idiopathic SNHL. This will be done on the understanding that the patient does not have any contraindications to oral steroids. A ceiling dose of 75 mg is important to minimise the risk of problems such as avascular necrosis of the hip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent referral to ENT is also required\u003C/strong\u003E, as sudden sensorineural hearing loss (SSNHL) is an otologic emergency. Specialist assessment is important to confirm the diagnosis, assess the degree of hearing loss, and consider further investigations such as \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI \u003C/strong\u003Eto exclude retrocochlear pathology, particularly vestibular schwannoma, which can present with unilateral SNHL.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin and other salicylates can cause ototoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E, but this is typically associated with high doses and presents as bilateral tinnitus or hearing loss, which is usually reversible upon cessation. At the low daily dose used for cardiovascular protection (100\u202fmg), aspirin is highly unlikely to be the cause of sudden unilateral hearing loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHence, the most appropriate action in this case is to commence high-dose corticosteroids immediately (prednisolone 1\u202fmg/kg to a maximum of 75\u202fmg daily) and urgently refer to ENT. Early treatment, ideally within 72 hours, offers the best chance of hearing recovery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Idiopathic sensorineural hearing loss requires immediate steroids and urgent ENT referral","High dose aspirin can produce ototoxicity that presents with tinnitus"],"references":["Chong A, Black D, Lee KJ, Edis N. Management of sudden sensorineural hearing loss. Aust J Gen Pract 2024;53 Suppl 1:S25\u20139. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/supplement-november/management-of-sudden-sensorineural-hearing-loss","Brien JA. Ototoxicity associated with salicylates. A brief review. Drug Saf. 1993 Aug;9(2):143-8. doi: 10.2165/00002018-199309020-00006. PMID: 8397891.","Anyah A, Mistry D, Kevern E, Markiewicz K. Idiopathic Sudden Sensorineural Hearing Loss: Average Time Elapsed Before Presentation to the Otolaryngologist and Effectiveness of Oral and/or Intratympanic Steroids in Late Presentations. Cureus. 2017;9(12):e1945. Published 2017 Dec 14. doi:10.7759/cureus.1945"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T20:18:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T20:19:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2587"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94985"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4